.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(223,96,'_oembed_time_5a8bed91a87424350983867bd3733e59','1553536816'),(228,132,'_edit_lock','1553632250:1'),(225,96,'_oembed_57d2ea60cfab018346105214a0c9539e','<blockquote class=\"embedly-card\" data-card-controls=\"1\" data-card-align=\"center\" data-card-theme=\"light\"><h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=stochastic+rsi\">stochastic rsi - YouTube</a></h4><p>Enjoy the videos and music you love, upload original content, and share it all with friends, family, and the world on YouTube.</p></blockquote><script async src=\"//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(226,96,'_oembed_time_57d2ea60cfab018346105214a0c9539e','1553536894'),(229,132,'_oembed_5de69b99054d0576e24a02d2a90003c6','<blockquote class=\"embedly-card\" data-card-controls=\"1\" data-card-align=\"center\" data-card-theme=\"light\"><h4><a href=\"https://www.myaccountingcourse.com/financial-ratios/free-cash-flow\">Free Cash Flow (FCF) Formula | Calculation | Example</a></h4><p>Free Cash Flow, often abbreviate FCF, is an efficiency and liquidity ratio that calculates the how much more cash a company generates than it uses to run and expand the business by subtracting the capital expenditures from the operating cash flow</p></blockquote><script async src=\"//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(230,132,'_oembed_time_5de69b99054d0576e24a02d2a90003c6','1553620862'),(236,134,'_edit_lock','1553618506:1'),(232,132,'_oembed_dadad22ca7d0dec5bb4ca0365b13a104','<blockquote class=\"embedly-card\" data-card-controls=\"1\" data-card-align=\"center\" data-card-theme=\"light\"><h4><a href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/freecashflow.asp\">Free Cash Flow - FCF</a></h4><p>Free cash flow represents the cash a company generates after cash outflows to support operations and maintain its capital assets. Unlike earnings or net income, free cash flow is a measure of profitability that excludes the non-cash expenses of the income statement and includes spending on equipment and assets as well as changes in working capital.</p></blockquote><script async src=\"//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(233,132,'_oembed_time_dadad22ca7d0dec5bb4ca0365b13a104','1553620865'),(234,132,'_oembed_21acebd1952f783f62824eb105d3aa00','<blockquote class=\"embedly-card\" data-card-controls=\"1\" data-card-align=\"center\" data-card-theme=\"light\"><h4><a href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/033015/what-formula-calculating-free-cash-flow.asp\">What Is the Formula for Calculating Free Cash Flow?</a></h4><p>Free cash flow is the cash a company produces through its operations, less the cost of expenditures on assets. In other words, free cash flow (FCF) is the cash left over after a company pays for its operating expenses and capital expenditures, also known as CAPEX.</p></blockquote><script async src=\"//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(235,132,'_oembed_time_21acebd1952f783f62824eb105d3aa00','1553620867'),(237,135,'_edit_lock','1553618676:1'),(238,135,'_oembed_a1c51610e120c457ad5ab075bbc776d2','<blockquote class=\"embedly-card\" data-card-controls=\"1\" data-card-align=\"center\" data-card-theme=\"light\"><h4><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fG3EUMArrU0\">How To Find And Pursue Your Passion | Think Out Loud With Jay Shetty</a></h4><p>Jay Shetty runs through a series of interactive workshops to help work towards pursuing your passions. Subscribe to HuffPost today: http://goo.gl/xW6HG Get More HuffPost Read: http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ Like: https://www.facebook.com/HuffingtonPost Follow: https://twitter.com/HuffingtonPost</p></blockquote><script async src=\"//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/platform.js\" charset=\"UTF-8\"></script>'),(239,135,'_oembed_time_a1c51610e120c457ad5ab075bbc776d2','1553618758'),(240,135,'_oembed_87438e7f477cbc60ef8ae2ae1d87b356','<blockquote class=\"embedly